entry.sense:
1. waOaI 
as syn. with waEada; 
imperative Uih. with the h of silence added; fem. corroborated form of the imperative Uin-a; of which last, see a curious ex. in the end of article HarofN AlOalifi, in the Mughnee.

wabolN 
Violent rain, consisting of large drops; 
as also waAbilN↓; (Ḳ;) a heavy rain.

miyvaAqN: 
see mawoviqN; 
and Jel, &c., in ii. 60 and 87.

10. Aisotawoxamahu 
He found it (food) to be unwholesome; 
as also tawax-amahu↓: (JK, Ḳ:) he found it (a land) to be insalubrious: (TA:) he found it (a country or town) to disagree with its inhabitants. (Ṣ, Mṣb.)

warikN 
What is above the thigh; 
[the haunch; or hip; and often signifying only the hip-bone; and the hip as meaning the joint of the thigh?] (Ṣ, Ḳ, &c.)

1. waraI, aor. yariI, 
inf. n. waroIN [and wuriI-N and riyapN, Ḳ]; and wariIa, aor. yariI; 
and OaworaI↓; It (a zanod) produced its fire. (Mṣb.)

Aall-ehu mino waraAYika God is seeking after thee, and watching, or lying in wait, for thee. (Ḥam, p. 206.) 
See also an ex. in the first paragraph {1} 
of art. ftl.

wasaEa Ealayohi rizoqahu, aor. yawosaEu; 
and OawosaEahu↓, 
and was-aEahu↓; He (God) made his means of subsistence ample and abundant. (Mṣb.)

waXalN, applied to water: 
see an ex. voce sajaEa; 
and another in a verse cited voce daqalN; 
and another voce raAXiHN.

And waSala Habolahu, 
inf. n. waSolN and SilapN; 
and waASala↓ Habolahu: [He made close his bond of love, by affectionate conduct]. (M.)

1. waqafa 
He was, or became, still, or stationary; (Mṣb;) [he stood still;] he continued standing: (Ḳ:) and [simply] he stood; 
contr. of jalasa. (TA.)

wukonapN certainly means, sometimes, A bird's nest, wherever it be: 
see an ex. in the first paragraph {1} 
of art. gdw.

wilaAfN, 
for UilaAfN: 
see Oalifahu.

wal-aI duburahu and wal-aAhu duburahu; 
see duburN, 
and see three phrases voce canabN.

4. Oawohamahu 
He made him to think [or imagine a thing]; 
as also wah-amahu↓. (Ṣ, Ḳ.) Oawohamahu kacaA He made him to think, or suspect, such a thing. (MA.)

wahonaAnapN 
I. q. wanaApN, q. v.; 
and see OanaApN.
